We recommended and Management agreed to instruct the – 

Municipal Treasurer to – 

i.	xxx;









ii.	update the data in the RPTAR and reflect the running balance based on the assessment roll provided by the Municipal Assessor’s Office;





















iii.	prepare duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year based on the RPTAR and furnish the Municipal Accountant;




















iv.	coordinate with the Provincial Government of Bataan regarding the technical assistance to set up the linkage of the PATAS to the MTO to utilize the system in accordance with the existing Memorandum of Agreement (MOA); and
















v.	implement procedures and strategies on how to further improve collection efficiency through publishing yearly the notice of delinquency once a week for two consecutive weeks in a newspaper of general circulation; and including remarks/statement regarding the reason/s for non-collection or non-payment in the certified list of all real property tax delinquencies which remained uncollected or unpaid for at least one year, with a request for assistance in the enforcement of the remedies for collection submitted to the Sanggunian.



Municipal Accountant to consider requesting to Commission on Audit’s Accounting Systems Development and Other Services Office (ASDOSO) under the Government Accountancy Sector the installation of the latest version of enhanced New Government Accounting System (e-NGAS) which will aid them in recording transactions, financial statement preparation, among others, but also to facilitate the maintenance of Subsidiary Ledgers related to RPT/ SET Receivables to provide reconciliation with records of MTO as well as to support the balance reflected in the financial statements.

We recommended and Management agreed to –

a.	On the electricity of market -

•	consider to (i) transfer the electricity connections of market stalls directly to PENELCO in order to save time, fund and effort from reading sub-meters, collecting payments, recording of receivables and payments and enforcing actions against defaulting owners of sub-meters; or (ii) to create/craft clear-cut/written and approved guidelines for the detailed procedures in the over-all operations in the distribution, collection and recording of electric consumption in the Orion Public Market and the duties and responsibilities of the assigned personnel/employees, which shall include, (without prejudice to Management’s decision in incorporating additional controls):

•	improved procedures of electric meter reading and period when to conduct the reading, computation of rates, deadline of payments and penalties of late payments of electricity consumption;

•	the preparation of Summary of Billings and individual billing statement as signed by the preparer and to be submitted to the MTO for the counterchecking of its computation;



•	the manner of distribution of copies of pre-numbered individual billing statements or statement of accounts, to wit:

Original – Consumer/Owner of sub-meter
Duplicate – COA (as attachment to OR/AF No. 51)
Triplicate – Market file

•	the method of setting up the receivables based on the computed and approved electricity billings of a given month and the maintenance of the subsidiary ledger per lessee/owner of sub-meter by the Municipal Accountant’s Office;

•	the periodic reconciliation of MTO’s records related to market collection with the subsidiary ledger maintained in the Municipal Accountant’s Office;

•	xxx;

•	the recording of electricity collections by crediting electricity expenses (to remove the electricity expenses of stallholders in the records of Market); 

•	the salaries/wages of person/s directly involve in Orion Public Market and other expenses directly incurred with the electricity connection, disconnection and reconnection; and

•	instruct the Head of the Market Operations to guarantee the strict enforcement of policies, rules and regulations for Market-Electricity operations.

b.	instruct the Municipal Accountant to (i) maintain subsidiary records for the LEEs; and (ii) prepare a Statement of Financial Condition, Statement of Financial Performance and Statement of Cash Flows for the market and other economic enterprises of the Municipality to (a) determine whether the income generated by the public utilities or economic enterprises are sufficient to meet their respective operating costs; and (b) provide adequate information as to the assets, liabilities, equity, receipts, transfers and expenditures of each special account;

c.	direct the Market Committee and other market officials to (i) conduct benchmarking to other LGUs with successful market operations and consider the adoption of their strategies to gradually improve the market operations and balance the protection of Municipality, legitimate stallholders and its constituent’s interests; (ii) revise pertinent sections of the 2003 Market Code which were found to be outdated (e.g. rental rates) after proper consultation with stallholders via public hearing/s; and (iii) strictly implement the stipulations of the Market Code to protect government’s welfare;

d.	if the budget permits, consider the appointment of full-time Market Administrator;

e.	specify in the Market Code the officials who shall spearhead in the revision and finalization of contract of lease per stallholder; and

f.	consider the inclusion of performance of periodic inspection and review of municipal market operations and guaranteeing that market operations are economically viable and self-reliant in the duties and responsibilities of Market Committee.

We reiterated prior year’s recommendation and Management agreed to –

a.	instruct the Solid Waste Management Board (SWMB) to –

•	direct the 23 Punong Barangays during their quarterly meetings to (i) strictly implement measures to ensure compliance with mandatory segregation at source (household level); and (ii) ensure that the barangay Materials Recovery Facility (MRF) are properly labeled as to type of waste, covered to prevent scattering of litter and the functionality thereof;

•	review the SWMP every two years or as the need arises for purposes of ensuring its sustainability, viability, effectiveness and relevance in relation to local and international developments in the field of solid waste management; 

•	review the municipality’s existing Comprehensive Solid Waste Management Code (Municipal Ordinance 12-020-077 dated October 16, 2012 for updating and inclusion of programs to be implemented with corresponding assigned committees with members’ duties and responsibilities; and

•	xxx;



b.	direct the designated Municipal Environment and Natural Resources Officer (MENRO) to –

•	conduct Waste Analysis and Characterization Study (WACS) to be used in the updating of the Solid Waste Management Plan (SWMP) and endorse the updating of the plan incorporating the COVID-19 waste management to SWMB; and

•	revisit the MOA with MCWMC to (i) request for the amendment on xxx; and (ii) xxx;



c.	instruct the MEO and designated MENRO to ensure the monitoring of the utilization of the facilities in the central MRF that these were being used in accordance with its intended usage and compliant with environmental standards; and

d.	prioritize the establishment of MENRO Office and appoint a full-time Officer to be able to address various compliances on solid waste management as well as other environmental standards compliance being implemented.

We also recommended that the Solid Waste Management Board, with the aid of the Sanggunian Bayan (SB), particularly the Committee on Environment, revisit all the existing ordinances of the Municipality related to the environment and waste management for its revision, if needed, in accordance with the issued republic acts, for their doable and proper implementation.

We recommended that –

(a)    designate or assign a Local Population Officer;

(b)    include the designated or assigned Local Population Officer in the GAD Committee; 


(c)    incorporate in the GAD, programs to supplement sex education in Department of Education (DepEd) modules with the use of interactive forms of communication; and

(d)    incorporate in the GAD other responsible parenthood and reproductive health programs to address teenage pregnancies.

